gent.yaml` are silently dropped**\n\nFiles: `internal/daemon/agents.go` (lines 307–339) and `hermes_bridge/tools.py` (lines 412–419)\n\nThe daemon reads `belayer_tools` from `agent.yaml` line-by-line and passes the list to the bridge as `BELAYER_TOOLS`. The Python bridge then builds `tools_to_register = BASELINE_TOOLS | set(allowed_tools)` and only registers tools that appear in `_HANDLER_FACTORIES`. If a tool name in `agent.yaml` has a typo or refers to a non-existent tool, both the Go daemon and the Python bridge silently ignore it — no warning, no error. The supervisor could be spawned without `belayer_spawn_agent` or `belayer_request_completion` with no indication of why. The daemon should at least log a warning for unrecognized tool names before passing them to the bridge.\n\n---\n\n**Bug 3 — `inTools = true` set before `break` on `belayer_tools: []` is dead/misleading code**\n\nFile: `internal/daemon/agents.go`, lines 322–325\n\n```go\nif trimmed == \"belayer_tools:\" || trimmed == \"belayer_tools: []\" {\n    inTools = true  // set here...\n    if trimmed == \"belayer_tools: []\" {\n        break        // ...but never read again after this break\n    }\n```\n\nSetting `inTools = true` immediately before unconditionally breaking is dead code. If YAML had a multi-key structure where `belayer_tools: []` appeared after a prior `belayer_tools:` block with collected tools, the `break` would exit the inner loop but `belayerTools` would already contain those tools — the `inTools = true` does nothing to clear them. For current well-formed templates this is benign, but it's a logic smell that would bite if the YAML format ever changes. The correct behavior for `belayer_tools: []` is to `break` without setting `inTools = true`, and `belayerTools` should be reset to `nil`/empty before breaking to make the intent explicit.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>92269</total_tokens><tool_uses>63</tool_uses><duration_ms>249037</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
